import { parse } from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/crawler-url-parser/crawler-url-parser.js";

describe("parse function with protocol handling", () => {
  it("should correctly parse a URL that already contains http:// protocol", () => {
    const result = parse("http://example.com");
    expect(result).not.toBeNull();
    expect(result?.url).toBe("http://example.com/");
    expect(result?.protocol).toBe("http:");
    expect(result?.host).toBe("example.com");
  });
});
```

Let me analyze more carefully. The mutation removes the `^` anchor from the regex in the `replace` call.

The code path is:
1. `baseUrlStr` is falsy/undefined
2. The URL doesn't match `/^\.*\/|^(?!localhost)\w:/`

For `http://example.com`, let me re-examine the mutated behavior. Without `^`, the regex `/(?!(?:\w+:)?\/\/)/` finds the first position where the lookahead succeeds.

At position 0: lookahead checks if string starting at 0 matches `(?:\w+:)?\/\/`. `http://` matches `\w+:\/\/`, so lookahead FAILS (negative lookahead).
At position 1: `ttp://` - `ttp:` matches `\w+:` and `//` matches `\/\/`, lookahead FAILS.
At position 2: `tp://` - same, FAILS.
At position 3: `p://` - same, FAILS.  
At position 4: `://` - `\w+:` needs at least one word char, `://` doesn't match, lookahead SUCCEEDS → inserts `http://` at position 4!

So `http://example.com` becomes `httphttp:////example.com` in the mutated version, which would fail to parse as a valid URL.

